<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<chapter xml:id="ch-the-chromatic-button-accordion" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>The Chromatic Button Accordion</title>
     <introduction>

      <p>This type of accordion (see picture in Section 2.1) is characterised by the Buttons on the Right hand (Treble Side). The Treble buttons are arranged chromatically in a number of columns. In the accordion I am considering in this manual, there are 5 columns, but the last two, nearest the bellows, duplicate notes already found in the first three columns. The additional columns allow more options  in fingering. There are some smaller accordions that have only the first three columns without duplication. Section 2.2 shows a detailed arrangement of the keys on the treble side.</p> 
      <p>In the most common type of chromatic accordion, with a Stradella bass, the bass and chord buttons are arranged in six columns parallel to the bellows. The columns are: Counter Bass, Bass, Major Chord, Minor Chord, 7th Chord and Diminished Chord. The basses are arranged in intervals of a fifth  and the chords are built on the second row of basses. See Section 2.4 for detailed arrangement of the keys on Stradella Bass instrument. </p> <p> In the Free Bass accordion the outer-most 4 columns are arranged chromatically. In the C System the left hand keyboard mirrors the treble key arrangement allowing much more freedom of Chord choice and construction than on a Stradella bass instrument at the expenditure, initially, of more mental effort by the player. See Section 2.3 the Free-Bass layout.</p>
      <p>The Chromatic Button Accordion is  is isomorphic, meaning a chord or scale "shape" retains the exact same shape regardless of the key you are in or where you are on the keyboard. Knowledge of one type of scale or chord means that you have knowledge of all chords or scales of that identity since the shape can be moved anywhere on the keyboard taking the name of the "Root" of the chord or scale.</p> 
      
    </introduction>
       



